{{Infobox person | name = Wim Hof | image = Wim_Hof.jpg | caption = Hof immersed in an ice bath, 2007 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|4|20|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Sittard|Sittard, Limburg]], Netherlands | nickname = The Iceman | children = 6 | occupation = [[extreme sport|Extreme athlete]] }} '''Wim Hof''' (born 20 April 1959), also known as '''The Iceman''', is a Dutch [[extreme sport|extreme athlete]] noted for his ability to withstand extreme cold, which he attributes to his Wim Hof Method (WHM) breathing techniques.<ref name="Erik Hedegaard" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pepijnvanerp.nl/2016/01/wim-hof-method/|title=Wim Hof's Cold Trickery – Pepijn van Erp|website=www.pepijnvanerp.nl|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref><ref>Joseph Angier, 7 March 2008, ABC News, [http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=4393377 Iceman on Everest: 'It Was Easy'], Accessed 14 April 2014</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=FEHILY|first1=TOBY|title=What Doesn’t Kill Us, To Be a Machine: books on extreme measures|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/what-doesnt-kill-us-to-be-a-machine-books-on-extreme-measures/news-story/a41089eaf5fb3f83a7cfab476c23ae8c|accessdate=3 November 2017|date=7 October 2017}}</ref> Hof says that the WHM can treat or help alleviate symptoms of illnesses such as [[multiple sclerosis]], [[arthritis]], [[diabetes]], [[clinical depression]], [[anxiety]], [[bipolar disorder]], and [[cancer]].<ref name="Erik Hedegaard" />
Hof has set out to spread the potential health benefits of his breathing techniques, working with scientists around the world to prove that his techniques work.<ref>[https://www.vice.com/en_dk/article/iceman Iceman] [[Vice Media]]</ref> A study published in the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] stated that by consciously [[Hyperventilation|hyperventilating]], Hof can increase his [[heart rate]], [[adrenaline]] levels, and blood alkalinity.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kox M, van Eijk LT, Zwaag J, van den Wildenberg J, GJ Sweep FC, van der Hoeven JG, Pickkers P |date=May 20, 2014 |title=Voluntary activation of the sympathetic nervous system and attenuation of the innate immune response in humans |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/111/20/7379.full |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America |volume=111 |issue=20 |pages=7379–7384 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1322174111 |pmc=4034215 |access-date=January 28, 2017 |pmid=24799686}}</ref> Hof is the subject of ''[[The New York Times]]'' bestselling book ''What Doesn't Kill Us'', which tells the story of how the investigative journalist [[Scott Carney]] took an assignment to debunk the WHM but ended up learning Hof's techniques.
== Early life == Hof was born in [[Sittard|Sittard, Limburg]], [[Netherlands]] as one of nine children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.scottcarney.com/article/the-iceman-commeth/|title=The Iceman Cometh - scottcarney.com|newspaper=scottcarney.com|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-09}}</ref> When he was 17 he felt a sudden urge to jump into the freezing cold water of the [[List_of_parks_in_Amsterdam#Beatrixpark|Beatrixpark]] canal.<ref>[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Np0jGp6442A Joe Rogan Experience #712 - Wim Hof] [[YouTube]]</ref><ref name="Erik Hedegaard">''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/wim-hof-method-the-iceman-on-key-to-healthy-life-w510956 Wim Hof Says He Holds the Key to a Healthy Life – But Will Anyone Listen?] Erik Hedegaard, November 16, 2017</ref>
== Records == [[File:Wim Hof at Theater Amsterdam.jpg|thumb|Hof at a 2015 event]] Hof holds 26 [[world record]]s, including one for longest ice bath.<ref>[http://www.hofoutdoor.nl/iceman Background information on Hof on hofoutdoor.nl], accessed 20 May 2018</ref> In 2007 he climbed to 7200m/23600 feet altitude at [[Mount Everest]] wearing nothing but shorts and shoes, but failed to reach the summit due to a recurring foot injury.<ref>[http://www.mounteverest.net/news.php?id=15688 Dutch Iceman to climb Everest in shorts: It's all about the inner fire], MountEverest.net</ref><ref> ''[[The Age]]'', 29 May 2007. [http://www.theage.com.au/news/world/everest-climber-falls-short/2007/05/28/1180205165881.html Everest climber falls short]</ref> In 2008 he broke his previous world record by staying immersed in ice for 1 hour, 13 minutes and 48 seconds at [[Guinness World Records]] 2008.{{Citation needed|date = December 2015}} The night before, he performed the feat on the ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today Show]]''.{{Citation needed|date = December 2015}}
In February 2009 Hof reached the top of [[Mount Kilimanjaro]] within two days wearing only shorts.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bb2jJsi1Ykc|title=Iceman Wim Hof on Kilimanjaro Summit|date=14 February 2009|work=YouTube|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> Hof completed a [[marathon]] above the [[arctic circle]] in [[Finland]], in temperatures close to {{convert|-20|C|F}}. Dressed in nothing but shorts, Hof finished in 5 hours and 25 minutes. The challenge was filmed by Firecrackerfilms, who make productions for [[BBC]], [[Channel 4]] and [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]].<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BpKXE2lm4t0|title=Daredevils: The Ice Man|date=18 September 2009|work=YouTube|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>
In 2011 Hof again broke the ice endurance record by standing fully immersed in ice for 1 hour and 44 minutes in [[Tokyo, Japan]].<ref name="AT5-2010">{{cite news |url = http://www.at5.nl/artikelen/29805/iceman-wim-hof-breekt-wereldrecord-ijsstaan |title = 'Iceman' Wim Hof breekt wereldrecord ijsstaan |trans-title='Ice man' Wim Hof breaks world record for staying in ice water |language = Dutch |work = [[AT5|AT5 Nieuws]] |location = [[Amsterdam]] |date = 3 January 2010 |accessdate = 10 May 2012 |quote = ''Hij stond 1 uur en 44 minuten tot en met zijn nek in het ijs'' (He stood up to his neck in ice water for 1 hour and 44 minutes) }}</ref>
In 2011 Hof broke the ice endurance record twice, in [[Inzell]] in February and in [[New York City]] in November, setting a new Guinness World Record of 1 hour, 52 minutes, and 42 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innerfire.nl/en-home|title=Innerfire - Wim Hof, The Iceman - Innerfire|author=Innerfire|publisher=|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> In September, Hof ran a full marathon in the [[Namib Desert]] without water, under the supervision of Dr. Thijs Eijsvogels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innerfire.nl/wim-hof-blog|title=Wim Hof Blog|author=Innerfire|publisher=|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>
== Breathing Method == There are many variations of the Wim Hof Method. The basic version consists of three phases as follows:
;Controlled hyperventilation: The first phase involves 30 cycles of breathing. Each cycle goes as follows: take a powerful breath in, fully filling the lungs. Breathe out by passively releasing the breath, but not actively exhaling. Repeat this cycle at a steady rapid pace thirty times. Hof says that this form of [[hyperventilation]] may lead to [[Paresthesia|tingling sensations]] or [[Lightheadedness|light-headedness]]. ;Exhalation: After completion of the 30 cycles of controlled hyperventilation, take another deep breath in, and let it out completely. Hold the breath for as long as possible. ;Breath retention: When strong urges to breathe occur, take a full deep breath in. Hold the breath for around 15 - 20 seconds and let it go. The body may experience a normal head-rush sensation.
These three phases may be repeated for three consecutive rounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icemanwimhof.com/wim-hof-exercises|title=Wim Hof exercises - Wim Hof, The Iceman - Innerfire|last=Innerfire|website=www.icemanwimhof.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref>
==Publications== *''Klimmen in stilte'', 1998, {{ISBN|9789069634395}} *''De top bereiken is je angst overwinnen'', 2000, {{ISBN|9789055991136}} *''Becoming the Iceman'', 2011, {{ISBN|9781937600464}}[[File:Becoming the Iceman - Cover.jpg|thumb|right|248x248px|''Becoming the Iceman'' cover]] *''[[Scott_Carney#What_Doesn't_Kill_Us|What Doesn't Kill Us]]'', 2017, {{ISBN|1623366909}}
== Personal life == Hof has six children, four of them with his first wife who committed suicide in 1995,<ref>{{Citation|last=PowerfulJRE|title=Joe Rogan Experience #712 - Wim Hof|date=2015-10-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Np0jGp6442A|accessdate=2017-02-24}}</ref> and a son, born in 2003 to his second wife. Also a son in 2017.<ref name="Innerfire">{{cite web|url=http://www.innerfire.nl/the-iceman|title=Innerfire - Wim Hof, The Iceman - Innerfire|author=Innerfire|publisher=|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> Hof feels that sadness over the loss of his first wife was formative in leading him to develop techniques to face low temperature environments.<ref name="Innerfire" />
== Controversies == Wim Hof has been blamed by relatives of four men who separately drowned in 2015 and 2016 when practicing his breathing exercise. They died after suffering [[shallow water blackout]]s in swimming pools.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gezondheid.eenvandaag.nl/tv-items/67565/_iceman_onder_vuur |title='Iceman' onder vuur |first1=Fannie |last1=Tijmstra |first2=Loes |last2=Bomers |date=10 June 2016 |publisher=''[[EenVandaag]]'' |language=Dutch |access-date=20 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parool.nl/binnenland/-iceman-oefening-eist-opnieuw-leven~a4332186 |title='Iceman'-oefening eist opnieuw leven |first1=Roelf Jan |last1=Duin |date=2 July 2016 |publisher=''[[Het Parool]]''|language=Dutch |access-date=20 July 2016 }}</ref> Wim Hof advises to do the exercises in a safe manner and location.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wimhofmethod.com/pages/practice-the-method|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129181133/https://www.wimhofmethod.com/pages/practice-the-method|archivedate=29 November 2016|deadurl=no |title=Practice the Wim Hof Method|website=Wim Hof Method|date= |author= |accessdate= 26 July 2017}}</ref>
